ated molecular methods, scientists are upending conventional wisdom about the role of microbes in every part of the world. Their research reveals the resilience and complexity of the indigenous microbial communities that contribute to the flavor and safety of cheese. One experiment at a time, these dynamic scientists, cheesemakers, and dairy farmers are reinventing the wheel.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 20. Sep 2019) 0aCheese industry. 0aCheesexMicrobiology. 0aCheesemakers. 0aCheesemakingxTechnological innovations. 0aCheesemaking. 0aDairy farmingxTechnological innovations. 0aRaw milkxMicrobiology. 4acheese connoisseurs. 4acheese history. 4acheesemakers. 4acheesemaking techniques. 4acheesemaking. 4achefs. 4acuisine. 4adairy farmers. 4afamous cheeses. 4afarm life. 4aflavor and safety. 4afood and cooking. 4afood historian. 4afrance. 4ahistory of cheese. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh1 aPercival, Francis, eauthor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018z978311063539308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2017z978311066755408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018z978311065859040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520964464423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520964464.jpg  a978-3-11-063539-3  UC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-065859-0  UCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018c2017d2018  a978-3-11-066755-4  UC Press eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles